From 59f1a51ed358ac5d2445e79ace7ccc16e331ab40 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Nadia Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@ik.me>
Date: Tue, 5 May 2026 01:54:26 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 094/174] mm: PGCL anon rmap convention unified at one event
 per PTE (Option A)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The 5 PVMW callback fixes from Phase-2b (commits c378da12..f3b87d6a)
adopted a "one rmap event per kernel-page mapping site" convention
(Option B) for the rmap walkers, while do_anonymous_page's clustering
fault path also went to Option B.  But the per-PTE fault helpers,
copy_pte_range PGCL anon batch, zap_present_ptes PGCL anon batch, and
do_wp_page COW clustering all kept the legacy "one rmap event per PTE"
convention (Option A).

The fracture was masked on x86_64+aarch64 because production kernels
build with CONFIG_DEBUG_VM=n, which gates is_check_pages_enabled() —
free_page_is_bad() and check_new_page_bad() both silently skip the
_mapcount sanity check, so over- or under-decremented mapcounts cycle
through the buddy allocator without complaint.  ppc64_defconfig (which
the 80-cell matrix exercises) enables DEBUG_VM and surfaces the
asymmetry as `BUG: Bad page state in process munlock01 mapcount:-15`
on free: 1 add (Option B) vs 16 removes (per-PTE zap-batch loop) =
mapcount underflow by 15.

Earlier "Bug 6" attempts to convert zap_present_ptes alone (or zap +
copy_pte_range) cascaded into 38 SHMEM `BUG: Bad page cache` events
on x86_64+aarch64: anon pages with previously-leaked positive
mapcount cycled through buddy and were re-allocated as SHMEM cache
entries, where folio_mapped() returned true at filemap_unaccount_folio
time.  Trace data showed an 8.7k-to-952 (9:1) REM:ADD asymmetry on
anon folios under partial-fix builds.

Pick Option A everywhere instead.

do_anonymous_page (mm/memory.c): folio_add_new_anon_rmap sets _mapcount
to 0 (one mapping); after the for-loop has installed `rss` sub-PTEs,
add (rss - 1) more mapcounts directly via atomic_add and bump
NR_ANON_MAPPED by the same delta.  Refcount and MM_ANONPAGES were
already MMUPAGE-granular and unchanged.

PVMW callbacks (mm/rmap.c, mm/migrate.c): __folio_remove_rmap and
__folio_add_rmap on a non-large folio always touch _mapcount by ±1
regardless of nr_pages, so loop the call nr_pages times per yield in
try_to_unmap_one (line 2429), try_to_migrate_one (line 2856), and
remove_migration_pte (mm/migrate.c) — for both anon and file folios.
For anon migration restore, advance the address by i*MMUPAGE_SIZE so
folio_add_anon_rmap_pte's PageAnonExclusive bookkeeping resolves to
the correct sub-page.

folio_referenced_one (mm/rmap.c): pra->mapcount is now in PTE units,
so drop `(nr + PAGE_MMUCOUNT - 1) >> PAGE_MMUSHIFT` (Option B
ceiling-divide) in favor of `pra->mapcount -= nr` (Option A direct).
The VM_LOCKED branch keeps `ptes++` as a kernel-page-yield count
(compared to pvmw.nr_pages = folio_nr_pages) but switches the
mapcount-- to `-= pvmw.nr_mmupages` for PTE-unit accounting.
page_vma_mkclean_one doesn't touch _mapcount; no change.

try_to_unmap_one RSS sites (mm/rmap.c lines 2291, 2306, 2394): the
HWPOISON, discarded-PTE, and swap-anon paths each cleared nr_pages
PTEs but only decremented MM_ANONPAGES/mm_counter(folio) by 1.  Switch
to add_mm_counter(... -nr_pages).  The swap path's MM_SWAPENTS still
increments by 1 (set_pte_at line 2413 only writes one swap entry per
yield) — a pre-existing PGCL swap quirk where nr_pages-1 sub-PTEs are
cleared without swap-entry replacement; left for a follow-up since
the LTP matrix exercises no swap pressure.

Untouched (already Option A-compatible):
- copy_pte_range PGCL anon batch (line 1216 atomic_add(nr-1) for fork)
- zap_present_ptes PGCL anon batch (line 1814 loop for unmap)
- do_wp_page COW clustering (lines 4194/4206)
- set_pte_range / folio_add_file_rmap_ptes for FILE/SHMEM folios
- _entire_mapcount / large-folio paths (Options A and B coincide for
  large-folio rmap since all sub-pages share one struct page that was
  already incremented per kernel page in the fault path)

Verified on PGCL=4 (LTP results; zero kernel BUG/Oops/WARNING):
- x86_64: 71p/0f/28s — exact baseline match
- aarch64: 70p/0f/31s — exact baseline match
- ppc64: 74p/0f/27s — exact baseline match;
  munlock01 mapcount:-15 BUG ELIMINATED (was several BUGs per matrix
  cell baseline, all from the do_anonymous_page Option B vs zap-batch
  Option A asymmetry).

Signed-off-by: Nadia Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@gmail.com>

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 mm/memory.c  | 26 ++++++++--------
 mm/migrate.c | 20 +++++++++----
 mm/rmap.c    | 84 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++----------------------
 3 files changed, 75 insertions(+), 55 deletions(-)

diff --git a/mm/memory.c b/mm/memory.c
index ed81cd52088a..03c507245151 100644
--- a/mm/memory.c
+++ b/mm/memory.c
@@ -5907,22 +5907,20 @@ static vm_fault_t do_anonymous_page(struct vm_fault *vmf)
 			rss++;
 		}
 		/*
-		 * Adjust refcount for the extra PTEs created by fault-around.
-		 * folio_add_new_anon_rmap already set _mapcount = 0 (= 1
-		 * mapping = 1 kernel page) which is correct under PGCL: even
-		 * though we just installed PAGE_MMUCOUNT sub-page PTEs, they
-		 * collectively represent ONE mapping of this kernel page from
-		 * this VMA.  The walker (page_vma_mapped_walk) yields once
-		 * per kernel page, and try_to_unmap_one decrements _mapcount
-		 * once per yield; the previous +(rss-1) compensation that
-		 * matched a per-PTE walker is no longer needed.
-		 *
-		 * Refcount remains MMUPAGE-granular (one per PTE) since each
-		 * PTE-level operation in the unmap path takes one reference.
-		 * RSS counter is also MMUPAGE-granular.
+		 * PGCL convention (Option A): one rmap event per PTE.
+		 * folio_add_new_anon_rmap above set _mapcount = 0 (= 1 mapping)
+		 * for the first sub-PTE.  Add (rss - 1) more so mapcount equals
+		 * the number of sub-PTEs actually installed.  Per-PTE unmap paths
+		 * (zap_present_ptes anon-batch loop, do_wp_page COW clustering,
+		 * PVMW callbacks consuming nr_mmupages) decrement once per PTE,
+		 * so this keeps mapcount accounting balanced across fault → fork
+		 * → unmap.  Refcount and MM_ANONPAGES are also MMUPAGE-granular.
 		 */
-		if (rss > 1)
+		if (rss > 1) {
 			folio_ref_add(folio, rss - 1);
+			atomic_add(rss - 1, &folio->_mapcount);
+			lruvec_stat_mod_folio(folio, NR_ANON_MAPPED, rss - 1);
+		}
 		/* Fix RSS: we added 1 above (nr_pages), need rss total */
 		add_mm_counter(vma->vm_mm, MM_ANONPAGES, rss - 1);
 		update_mmu_cache_range(vmf, vma, addr, vmf->pte, 1);
diff --git a/mm/migrate.c b/mm/migrate.c
index 4edc3279a231..25360c19c3ac 100644
--- a/mm/migrate.c
+++ b/mm/migrate.c
@@ -450,11 +450,21 @@ static bool remove_migration_pte(struct folio *folio,
 		} else
 #endif
 		{
-			if (folio_test_anon(folio))
-				folio_add_anon_rmap_pte(folio, new, vma,
-							pvmw.address, rmap_flags);
-			else
-				folio_add_file_rmap_pte(folio, new, vma);
+			/*
+			 * PGCL Option A: one rmap event per PTE.  Loop the
+			 * add nr_pages times to match the nr_pages PTEs about
+			 * to be installed (set_ptes / set_pte_at loop below).
+			 * For non-PGCL nr_pages == 1.
+			 */
+			if (folio_test_anon(folio)) {
+				for (i = 0; i < nr_pages; i++)
+					folio_add_anon_rmap_pte(folio, new, vma,
+								pvmw.address + (unsigned long)i * MMUPAGE_SIZE,
+								rmap_flags);
+			} else {
+				for (i = 0; i < nr_pages; i++)
+					folio_add_file_rmap_pte(folio, new, vma);
+			}
 			if (unlikely(is_device_private_page(new))) {
 				/*
 				 * Device-private entries are non-present swap
diff --git a/mm/rmap.c b/mm/rmap.c
index cae5532a3383..7fd849910893 100644
--- a/mm/rmap.c
+++ b/mm/rmap.c
@@ -927,8 +927,16 @@ static bool folio_referenced_one(struct folio *folio,
 		nr = 1;
 
 		if (vma->vm_flags & VM_LOCKED) {
+			/*
+			 * ptes counts PVMW yields (= kernel-page mapping
+			 * sites visited).  pvmw.nr_pages is folio_nr_pages
+			 * (kernel pages), so this checks "have we seen all
+			 * kernel-page sites of the folio".  pra->mapcount
+			 * under PGCL Option A is in PTE units, so decrement
+			 * by pvmw.nr_mmupages per yield.
+			 */
 			ptes++;
-			pra->mapcount--;
+			pra->mapcount -= pvmw.pte ? pvmw.nr_mmupages : 1;
 
 			/* Only mlock fully mapped pages */
 			if (pvmw.pte && ptes != pvmw.nr_pages)
@@ -1002,17 +1010,14 @@ static bool folio_referenced_one(struct folio *folio,
 		}
 
 		/*
-		 * ptes accumulates MMUPAGE PTE counts (nr is MMUPAGE-granular
-		 * from folio_pte_batch / from the nr=1 default for the PMD
-		 * and non-large-folio paths).  pra->mapcount is in kernel-
-		 * page-mapping units (each kernel page mapped in a VMA is one
-		 * rmap event); convert nr by ceiling-dividing by PAGE_MMUCOUNT
-		 * so a partial-kernel-page batch (sub-page gap) still counts
-		 * as one observed mapping site.  For non-PGCL builds
-		 * PAGE_MMUCOUNT == 1 and this collapses to `pra->mapcount -= nr`.
+		 * PGCL Option A: pra->mapcount is in PTE units (one rmap event
+		 * per PTE).  ptes is the cumulative MMUPAGE PTE count from
+		 * folio_pte_batch (large folio) or 1 (non-large/PMD path).
+		 * Decrement pra->mapcount by the same nr.  For non-PGCL
+		 * (PAGE_MMUCOUNT == 1) this is the legacy form.
 		 */
 		ptes += nr;
-		pra->mapcount -= (nr + PAGE_MMUCOUNT - 1) >> PAGE_MMUSHIFT;
+		pra->mapcount -= nr;
 		/*
 		 * If we are sure that we batched the entire folio,
 		 * we can just optimize and stop right here.  Both sides in
@@ -2285,7 +2290,8 @@ static bool try_to_unmap_one(struct folio *folio, struct vm_area_struct *vma,
 				set_huge_pte_at(mm, address, pvmw.pte, pteval,
 						hsz);
 			} else {
-				dec_mm_counter(mm, mm_counter(folio));
+				/* PGCL Option A: per-PTE rss accounting */
+				add_mm_counter(mm, mm_counter(folio), -nr_pages);
 				set_pte_at(mm, address, pvmw.pte, pteval);
 			}
 		} else if (likely(pte_present(pteval)) && pte_unused(pteval) &&
@@ -2300,7 +2306,8 @@ static bool try_to_unmap_one(struct folio *folio, struct vm_area_struct *vma,
 			 * migration) will not expect userfaults on already
 			 * copied pages.
 			 */
-			dec_mm_counter(mm, mm_counter(folio));
+			/* PGCL Option A: per-PTE rss accounting */
+			add_mm_counter(mm, mm_counter(folio), -nr_pages);
 		} else if (folio_test_anon(folio)) {
 			swp_entry_t entry = page_swap_entry(subpage);
 			pte_t swp_pte;
@@ -2388,7 +2395,17 @@ static bool try_to_unmap_one(struct folio *folio, struct vm_area_struct *vma,
 					list_add(&mm->mmlist, &init_mm.mmlist);
 				spin_unlock(&mmlist_lock);
 			}
-			dec_mm_counter(mm, MM_ANONPAGES);
+			/*
+			 * PGCL Option A: nr_pages sub-PTEs were cleared by
+			 * get_and_clear_ptes above, but the swap path below
+			 * only writes ONE swap entry (set_pte_at).  Pending
+			 * proper PGCL swap-entry batching, account that
+			 * asymmetry directly: nr_pages anon pages "removed",
+			 * 1 swap entry installed.  The remaining nr_pages-1
+			 * sub-PTEs will fault as zero pages on next access
+			 * (pre-existing PGCL swap quirk).
+			 */
+			add_mm_counter(mm, MM_ANONPAGES, -nr_pages);
 			inc_mm_counter(mm, MM_SWAPENTS);
 			swp_pte = swp_entry_to_pte(entry);
 			if (anon_exclusive)
@@ -2424,11 +2441,16 @@ static bool try_to_unmap_one(struct folio *folio, struct vm_area_struct *vma,
 			hugetlb_remove_rmap(folio);
 		} else {
 			/*
-			 * One walker yield = one kernel page = one struct
-			 * page = one rmap event.  rmap APIs take kernel-page
-			 * count.  Refcount and RSS use MMUPAGE units (above).
+			 * PGCL Option A: one rmap event per PTE.  This yield
+			 * cleared nr_pages MMUPAGE PTEs, so drop nr_pages
+			 * mapcounts.  __folio_remove_rmap on a non-large folio
+			 * always decrements by 1 regardless of nr_pages, so
+			 * loop.  For non-PGCL (nr_pages always 1) this is the
+			 * legacy single call.
 			 */
-			folio_remove_rmap_pte(folio, subpage, vma);
+			unsigned int i;
+			for (i = 0; i < nr_pages; i++)
+				folio_remove_rmap_pte(folio, subpage, vma);
 		}
 		if (vma->vm_flags & VM_LOCKED)
 			mlock_drain_local();
@@ -2442,18 +2464,6 @@ static bool try_to_unmap_one(struct folio *folio, struct vm_area_struct *vma,
 		 * this yield (== pvmw.nr_mmupages, capped at PAGE_MMUCOUNT
 		 * by the walker), and folio_nr_pages * PAGE_MMUCOUNT is the
 		 * MMUPAGE PTE count of a fully-mapped folio.
-		 *
-		 * Do NOT collapse this to the kernel-page form
-		 * (max(1U, nr_pages >> PAGE_MMUSHIFT) == folio_nr_pages):
-		 * for a non-large folio (folio_nr_pages == 1) under PGCL,
-		 * any partial yield (1 <= nr_pages < PAGE_MMUCOUNT, e.g.
-		 * caused by a sub-page gap left by a partial munmap) would
-		 * round up to 1 and falsely trigger the early exit, leaving
-		 * later PTEs of the same folio unmapped — refcount and TLB
-		 * leak, folio appears unmapped to rmap.
-		 *
-		 * For non-PGCL builds (PAGE_MMUCOUNT == 1) this collapses to
-		 * `nr_pages == folio_nr_pages` — the legacy mainline check.
 		 */
 		if (nr_pages == folio_nr_pages(folio) * PAGE_MMUCOUNT)
 			goto walk_done;
@@ -2853,16 +2863,18 @@ static bool try_to_migrate_one(struct folio *folio, struct vm_area_struct *vma,
 			 */
 		}
 
-		if (unlikely(folio_test_hugetlb(folio)))
+		if (unlikely(folio_test_hugetlb(folio))) {
 			hugetlb_remove_rmap(folio);
-		else
+		} else {
 			/*
-			 * One walker yield = one kernel page = one struct
-			 * page = one rmap event.  Refcount uses MMUPAGE
-			 * units (folio_put_refs nr_pages), _mapcount is
-			 * decremented exactly once per yield.
+			 * PGCL Option A: one rmap event per PTE.  This yield
+			 * cleared nr_pages MMUPAGE PTEs; loop the rmap drop
+			 * (non-large folios decrement only by 1 per call).
 			 */
-			folio_remove_rmap_pte(folio, subpage, vma);
+			unsigned int i;
+			for (i = 0; i < nr_pages; i++)
+				folio_remove_rmap_pte(folio, subpage, vma);
+		}
 		if (vma->vm_flags & VM_LOCKED)
 			mlock_drain_local();
 		folio_put_refs(folio, nr_pages);
